The quotation from Varro explains ‘ vicina refugit jurgia,’ where Bentley, with little authority, reads ‘refigit:’ “cum non unam aliquam litem sed plurative ‘jurgia' dixerit,” which is just what the aoristic use of the perfect tense expresses. Nune prece] ‘Prece’ may refer to that which one man gives to another3 and a gift is a sufficient title to a thing, if the giver has full legal capacity, and there is no fraud in the matter. ‘ Pretio,’ of course, means the title by purchase. ‘ Vi ' is possession by force, which gives no title. We read of forcible occupation fre- quently in country places. ‘ Morte ’ means the title which a man obtains by the testa- ment and death of a testator, or by the death and intestacy of an owner, added to the kinship os him who claims as heres.
